<DocsLayout title="Project 6: The Cloud Deploy" description="Build an inventory and taproom management system deployed to AWS with Terraform.">
  <h1 class="mb-2">Project 6: The Cloud Deploy</h1>
  <p class="text-xl text-primary font-medium mb-6">"I can deploy a containerised application to cloud infrastructure using Terraform."</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll build</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">An inventory and taproom management system for Tidal Brewing Co — Jake's craft brewery and taproom in Brunswick, Melbourne. Beer inventory (what's on tap, what's in the cellar), taproom event listings (trivia nights, live music, tap takeovers), and online ordering for pickup. A local brewery's digital presence with real inventory management behind it.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What's new (the +1)</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Infrastructure as Code. Until now, you've deployed to PaaS platforms — Netlify, Railway — where someone else manages the servers. This project changes that. You provision your own cloud infrastructure using Terraform: EC2 instances, S3 buckets, VPCs, security groups. You write <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">.tf</code> files describing the infrastructure you want, review the plan like a PR, and apply it.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">The shift from PaaS to IaaS is the shift from "deploy to someone else's servers" to "create and manage your own." You're responsible for the instance size, the network configuration, the firewall rules, and the monitoring. More control, more responsibility.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> PaaS platforms abstract away infrastructure. That's great — until you need control over instance size, network configuration, or cost. Terraform lets you define infrastructure in code, version it in git, review it in PRs, and reproduce it exactly. The same rigour you apply to application code now applies to the servers it runs on.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What success looks like</h2>
  <Checklist items={[
    "Terraform provisions an EC2 instance, S3 bucket, VPC, and security groups from code",
    "The application runs in Docker containers on EC2 with Nginx as a reverse proxy",
    "Jake can update the tap list through an admin interface and changes appear immediately",
    "Customers can browse the tap list, view events, and place pickup orders",
    "Secrets are stored in AWS Secrets Manager, not in .env files on the server",
    "CloudWatch monitors EC2 metrics and alerts on CPU spikes",
  ]} />

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll learn</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Write Terraform configuration to provision AWS infrastructure</li>
    <li>Deploy Docker containers to an EC2 instance</li>
    <li>Configure S3 for static asset storage</li>
    <li>Set up security groups and VPC networking</li>
    <li>Configure Nginx as a reverse proxy</li>
    <li>Store secrets in AWS Secrets Manager</li>
    <li>Monitor infrastructure with CloudWatch metrics and alarms</li>
    <li>Review <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform plan</code> output before applying changes</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Tech stack</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>React + FastAPI + PostgreSQL (in Docker on EC2)</li>
    <li>Terraform for infrastructure provisioning</li>
    <li>AWS free tier: EC2 t2.micro, S3, basic VPC</li>
    <li>Nginx reverse proxy</li>
    <li>AWS Secrets Manager for production secrets</li>
    <li>CloudWatch for monitoring</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Completed <a href="/web-dev/projects/5">Project 5</a> and <a href="/web-dev/checkpoints/after-p5">Checkpoint After Project 5</a></li>
    <li>An AWS free tier account (you'll set this up during the project)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Estimated time</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">2-3 weeks. The planning artifacts follow the established pattern. The new dimension — Terraform, AWS, and infrastructure management — adds significant setup and learning time beyond application development.</p>

